---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
import ChapterTable from "../../../components/ChapterTable.astro";
import Neighbors from "../../../components/Neighbors.astro";
---

<Layout title="Methodeutics" favicon="🔭">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to reading</a>

    <h1>🔭 Methodeutics</h1>

    <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 mb-6">The logic of inquiry. Statistics formalizes induction: how to generalize from observations. Methodeutics formalizes abduction: how to generate the next question. Peirce named both the mode (1878) and the field (1902). This is the textbook.</p>

    <h2>Modes of reasoning</h2>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Mode</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Edge</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Field</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Status</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Deduction</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Theory → Experiment</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Logic, mathematics</td><td class="text-gray-400">Formalized (Aristotle → Frege → Gödel)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Induction</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Experiment → Observation</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400"><a href="/reading/statistics/">Statistics</a></td><td class="text-gray-400">Formalized (Fisher → Neyman → Ramdas)</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Abduction</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Observation → Theory</td><td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Methodeutics</td><td class="text-green-400">This textbook</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Everyone does abduction. Doctors call it diagnosis. Engineers call it debugging. Detectives call it deduction (wrong, but Doyle didn't read Peirce). The pieces have always existed: philosophy, cognitive science, program analysis, causal inference, sequential testing.</p>

    <blockquote class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-6" style="border-left: 2px solid #555; padding-left: 1rem; font-style: italic;">
      <p>between vision and root<br/>
      blooms branches and shoots</p>
      <p>prune the duds<br/>
      thence more buds</p>
      <p>clues for felling<br/>
      perfuse its telling</p>
      <p>do trees need an arbor<br/>
      in light, soil and water?</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Chapters</h2>

    <p class="text-gray-400 mb-4 text-sm">Each chapter opens with a system that breaks under the previous chapter's tools. The breakage motivates the new concept. The textbook's structure embodies the method it teaches: the shape of the failure names the next chapter.</p>

    <h3 class="text-gray-400 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mt-6 mb-3">Part I: The trichotomy</h3>

    <ChapterTable chapters={[
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch01-three-modes/", title: "Three modes", desc: "Holmes and the dog that didn't bark. Doyle called it deduction. It isn't." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch02-security-uberty/", title: "Security and uberty", desc: "Popper says discovery has no logic. Peirce says it does, but admits it's insecure." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch03-eight-names/", title: "Eight names, one operation", desc: "Bi-abduction, figure-ground, equilibration, intervention. Six fields, zero cross-citation." },
    ]} icon="🔭" />

    <h3 class="text-gray-400 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mt-6 mb-3">Part II: The primitive</h3>

    <ChapterTable chapters={[
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch04-diff/", title: "Diff", desc: "A mechanic taps the alternator. The engine stalls. Two hypotheses fire. Where did they come from?" },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch05-bi-abduction/", title: "Bi-abduction", desc: "Infer runs on millions of lines. It infers the frame automatically. But bi-abduction is one path." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch06-tri-abduction/", title: "Tri-abduction", desc: "The program branches. Each branch changes different state. Bi-abduction can't handle the fork." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch07-economy-of-research/", title: "Economy of research", desc: "Ten hypotheses, budget for three experiments. Which three?" },
    ]} icon="🔭" startNumber={4} />

    <h3 class="text-gray-400 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mt-6 mb-3">Part III: The evidence</h3>

    <ChapterTable chapters={[
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch08-evidence-trajectory/", title: "Evidence has a trajectory", desc: "An A/B test says B is better. You ship. Six months later, B is worse. The snapshot lied." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch09-four-bins/", title: "Four bins", desc: "The trajectory oscillates. Is the system fighting itself, or is your measurement noisy?" },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch10-kill-conditions/", title: "The hypothesis graph", desc: "A monotone trend test fires but curvature is indeterminate. The failure mode is the next hypothesis." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch11-convergence/", title: "Convergence", desc: "Five sensor streams, each individually undetectable. Composed e-values classify the forcing pattern." },
    ]} icon="🔭" startNumber={8} />

    <h3 class="text-gray-400 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mt-6 mb-3">Part IV: The machine</h3>

    <ChapterTable chapters={[
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch12-protecting-the-loop/", title: "Protecting the loop", desc: "An agent confirms every hypothesis. It abduced from the data and tested on the same data." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch13-validating-claims/", title: "Validators", desc: "Four validator types, one interface. Empirical, structural, proof, counterexample." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch14-the-pipeline/", title: "The pipeline", desc: "Three witnesses (Infer, Voyager, IRM), each closing the loop in a different domain. None cite each other." },
      { href: "/reading/methodeutics/ch15-case-study/", title: "Case study", desc: "A system that searches without reasoning. It can perturb and observe but never asks why." },
    ]} icon="🔭" startNumber={12} />

    <h3 class="text-gray-400 text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mt-6 mb-3">Appendix: Primary Sources</h3>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="py-2 pr-1 w-6"></th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 px-2 text-gray-400">Appendix</th>
            <th class="py-2 px-2"></th>
            <th class="py-2 w-8"></th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-1 text-right text-gray-500 tabular-nums whitespace-nowrap align-top">A.</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-2 text-gray-300 align-top"><a href="/reading/methodeutics/appendix-peirce-1878/" style="background:transparent;padding:0">Deduction, Induction, and Hypothesis</a></td>
            <td class="py-2 px-2 text-gray-400 align-top">The bean syllogism. The 1878 origin of the trichotomy (Ch 1).</td>
            <td class="py-2 pl-1 align-top">
              <a href="/reading/methodeutics/appendix-peirce-1878/" style="background:transparent;padding:0">🔭</a>
            </td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-1 text-right text-gray-500 tabular-nums whitespace-nowrap align-top">B.</td>
            <td class="py-2 px-2 text-gray-300 align-top"><a href="/reading/methodeutics/appendix-peirce-1908/" style="background:transparent;padding:0">A Neglected Argument</a></td>
            <td class="py-2 px-2 text-gray-400 align-top">Musement and the three stages of inquiry. Foundations for Ch 2.</td>
            <td class="py-2 pl-1 align-top">
              <a href="/reading/methodeutics/appendix-peirce-1908/" style="background:transparent;padding:0">🔭</a>
            </td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Peirce's vocabulary</h2>

    <p>Terms coined or repurposed by <a href="/reading/scientific-method/peirce-1878/">Charles Sanders Peirce</a> (1839–1914) that do work in this textbook.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Term</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">Meaning</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Abduction</td><td class="text-gray-400">Inference from a surprising fact to an explanatory hypothesis. The only mode that introduces new ideas.</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Retroduction</td><td class="text-gray-400">Synonym. Leading backward, from effect to cause.</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Methodeutic</td><td class="text-gray-400">The third branch of logic: the study of methods of inquiry. (After speculative grammar and critical logic.)</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Uberty</td><td class="text-gray-400">The productive richness of a reasoning mode. Abduction: highest. Deduction: lowest. From Latin <em>ubertas</em> (fruitfulness).</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Security</td><td class="text-gray-400">The certainty of a reasoning mode. Inverse of uberty. Deduction: highest. Abduction: lowest.</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Economy of research</td><td class="text-gray-400">Hypothesis selection guided by cost-benefit: which experiment gives the most information per dollar?</td></tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800"><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Musement</td><td class="text-gray-400">Free, purposeless contemplation: "antipodal to vacancy and dreaminess." The pre-logical state from which abductive hypotheses emerge.</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Pragmaticism</td><td class="text-gray-400">The meaning of a concept is its conceivable practical effects. Renamed from pragmatism: "ugly enough to be safe from kidnappers."</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <p>All 15 chapters drafted and copyedited. Codex-reviewed to convergence.</p>

